{:output {:format "clj-kondo"}
 :parallel true
 :silent false

 ;; Clojure 1.12 method-value syntax (`^[] String/toUpperCase`, `Class/.instanceMethod`)
 ;; is an opt-in stylistic migration, not a defect: the codebase deliberately and
 ;; uniformly uses traditional interop, splint's own autocorrect cannot resolve the
 ;; receiver class (it emits a literal `CLASS` placeholder for instance calls), and the
 ;; rewrite would demand hand-authored `^[..]` param-tags at every one of ~500 call
 ;; sites. Adjudicated off; revisit only as a deliberate whole-repo modernisation.
 lint/prefer-method-values {:enabled false}

 ;; Skein is a long-lived daemon (weaver) that dynamically loads and resolves trusted
 ;; spool/config code. Every `(catch Throwable ...)` here is a deliberate boundary that
 ;; MUST see Errors too: dynamic `requiring-resolve`/`load-file`/EDN reads that wrap any
 ;; failure (incl. LinkageError/NoClassDefFoundError) in diagnostic ex-info and rethrow;
 ;; resilience nets on long-lived loops/threads (scheduler dispatch, event system) that
 ;; must never let one tick kill the runtime clock; cleanup handlers that `addSuppressed`
 ;; and rethrow the original; and process-boundary exit handlers. All 33 sites were
 ;; audited as load-bearing (narrowing to Exception would silently drop Error handling);
 ;; splint itself ships this rule `:safe false`, calling out mission-critical processes.
 ;; New lazy catches are caught by change review, not this rule. Adjudicated off.
 lint/catch-throwable {:enabled false}}
